1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:20,000
This is David Klein for the Smithsonian African American History and Culture Museum and the Library of Congress, Civil Rights History Project.

3
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:29,000
Today is Saturday, March 2, 2013, and I am in the City of San Francisco, California with Reverend Dr. Amos Sebrown.

4
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:34,000
Good afternoon. Good afternoon. So thank you so much for joining us and sharing your story.

5
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:38,000
My pleasure and great privilege to share with you.

6
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:44,000
And I am on channel 2 and Reverend Brann is on channel 1.

7
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Okay, no, I got it all covered. Okay, I can get into it.

8
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:57,000
So Reverend Brann, if we could just start, if you could tell us a little bit about where you were born and your family, your people,

9
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:03,000
and how that informed you at growing up as a young person.

10
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:23,000
I was born in Jackson, Mississippi, February 20, 1941, and according to the US Census, my great-great-grandfather, Patrick Brown,

11
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:35,000
was born and slave in Franklin County, Mississippi, in a community called Hamburg, East of Natchez.

12
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:52,000
And that area was one great dropping off point for slaves from about 1820 to 1850, and 4550.

13
00:01:52,000 --> 00:02:14,000
In fact, there was a terrific cholera epidemic around 1830 in Natchez, and these slaves who shipped down the river were quarantined out of a place called Fox in the Road, and that's East of Natchez.

14
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:22,000
So it was from that area that my great-great-grandfather was a slave.

15
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:38,000
And I have had that sense of history when I had the occasion of my aunt, my father's sister, sharing this information with me.

16
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Naturally, I was born in a segregated apartheid, south, and Mississippi when things were really difficult.

17
00:02:52,000 --> 00:03:14,000
In fact, it was commonplace for me to hear of the tales of legends, of Blacks being mysteriously unaccounted for in the Mississippi Delta, where my father passed a rule of churches.

18
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:25,000
In fact, my father succeeded Reverend George Lee in Holmes County, Mississippi, in a Baptist church.

19
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:39,000
Reverend George Lee was murdered in 1955, Mother Vapour, the same year that Emmett Teal was murdered.

20
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:45,000
My father was found on August 28, 1955.

21
00:03:45,000 --> 00:04:11,000
And I remember the instance in which a man named Edinor, a sharp shooter who confronted white man for having a affair with his wife, went to this honkettonk and restaurant in Holmes County, Mississippi,

22
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:17,000
to tell his wife that she had to come home and not work there anymore.

23
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:37,000
And when this white man jumped him and beat him up, this 28-year-old man, World War II veteran, went to his car, came back with his 22 rifle, and shot this white man dead with that 22 rifle.

24
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:49,000
He fled from the scene with his wife, and for 18 days he was on the run at about three to 400 white men.

25
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:57,000
The shaman would drop from moonshine liquor. This posse tried to apprehend him. They couldn't find him.

26
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:14,000
But it was a woman named Arinia Mallory, who was the first principal of the Saints Industrial School in Lexington, Mississippi.

27
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:21,000
That was a school, it was started as a high school, sponsored by the Church of God in Christ.

28
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:41,000
Church of God in Christ was founded by Charles Mason at the turn of the last century, about 19, about 1906, after he had gone down to Los Angeles to witness the Azuzra Street revival.

29
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:47,000
My point being, by giving all this background history is that this woman was so influential.

30
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:59,000
It was a vice president of the National Council of Negro Women, that group that was founded by the great woman Mary McLeod Batoon.

31
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:09,000
Dr. Mallory went to Edinowall and convinced him that he should turn himself in.

32
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:21,000
But before she met with him, she learned that he had killed two other deputies, shares.

33
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:38,000
And that meant that this black man murdered three white men and was on the run and did not turn himself in until this black woman convinced him to give up.

34
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Long short of it is that when he went to court, the judge, I'm sure in his mind, felt that in an Negro who would kill three white men in Mississippi, must have been crazy.

35
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:02,000
So he had an order for him to be examined over at the Whitfield Mental Institution.

36
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:11,000
And the record is that he was never tried and convicted.

37
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:30,000
He was released later and it was found out that he was a descendant, a child of one of the governors of Mississippi.

38
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:38,000
From 1909 to 1913, Governor Noll.

39
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:48,000
And I don't know if they had anything to do with his getting off, but he was never said to try and convicted.

40
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:53,000
He died a natural death in Fort Wayne, Indiana.

41
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:03,000
But I remember the child, the excitement, the serial reports of Edinowall killing these white men.

42
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:07,000
And what would happen if they called him?

43
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:09,000
Had to react to that.

44
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:17,000
Well, that story definitely was a great interest to me as a child.

45
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:29,000
And another story that impacted me was the murder of Emmett Till, both happening around the same time.

46
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:31,000
And then...

47
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:34,000
And you would have been about 11 at that time.

48
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:37,000
And here is the boy not much older than you.

49
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:38,000
Yes.

50
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:42,000
And so how did you react to that story?

51
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:45,000
I did. I reacted to those stories.

52
00:08:45,000 --> 00:08:58,000
My son is a school teacher, Miss Eserrandel, who was treasurer of the Jackson branch of NACP over 30 years.

53
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:07,000
One Sunday morning at the Ferris Street Baptist Church, which was one of the few churches that opened this door to end a civil rights activity.

54
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:08,000
What's the name of it again?

55
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:14,000
Ferris, F-A-R-I-S-H. Ferris Street Baptist Church.

56
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:19,000
Once on the morning she asked me, did I know what my name meant?

57
00:09:19,000 --> 00:09:22,000
I was eight years old then.

58
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:24,000
And I told her, no.

59
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:27,000
She said, your name means Amos.

60
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:29,000
That's a Hebrew word.

61
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:35,000
And it means the prophet who bears the burdens of the people.

62
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:38,000
And I never forgot that.

63
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:52,000
So that when I became aware of Edenore, I became aware of the liching of Emmett Till, Reverend George Lee.

64
00:09:52,000 --> 00:10:05,000
And when I became aware of a meeting that was held in Dallas, Texas in 1954, that my sister attended along with Mechler Evers.

65
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:20,000
It was at that meeting in 1954 that Shannon H. Tobias, who was chairman of the board of NACP, Corn the Frees, freed by 1963.

66
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:34,000
And when Gloria came back from that meeting with Mr. Evers, and I heard her telling what happened, I was all intrigued about this conversation that I had with her.

67
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:40,000
And she said, you know, in 1963, there would be no more segregation.

68
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:43,000
We'll be able to vote.

69
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:46,000
We'll have to sit in the back of the bus.

70
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:53,000
But we're going to have to work to make sure that it really happens.

71
00:10:53,000 --> 00:11:01,000
And I was excited about this change that was going to come because of what this man said in Dallas.

72
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:10,000
That I got involved and I organized the first Youth Council of NACP in 1955.

73
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:29,000
And after I organized that Youth Council, that spring of 1956, Mr. Evers asked my mother if I could travel with him to San Francisco,

74
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:43,000
to the National Convention of NACP, where I would have exposure with other young people from across the country, who were in civil rights activity under the umbrella of NACP Youth Movement.

75
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:47,000
That was my first time out of West.

76
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:54,000
Mr. Evers had just bought an old 1955 Oathsmobile. We called it the Blue Goose.

77
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:57,000
It didn't have air condition in that day.

78
00:11:57,000 --> 00:12:09,000
In fact, you had to use ice packs, bags of ice to put on the hood of the car to cool the engine as you went through the desert coming westward.

79
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:18,000
So that summer of 1956, the month of July, we came to San Francisco.

80
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:28,000
And never ever get when we approached that bay bridge and I saw all of this water after we had come up through the valley, you know, up San Francisco.

81
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:31,000
And I came to this great meeting.

82
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:41,000
I didn't have money to stay in hotels. I stayed with a family who were friends of my mother.

83
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:48,000
And her name was Hutchison. They lived up on Fulton Street, up near Fulton and the Visitora.

84
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:58,000
And I walked from Fulton and the Visitora every day to the meetings, to the night-lip hell mass meetings.

85
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:06,000
And it was my fortune to first hear Martin Luther King on youth night.

86
00:13:06,000 --> 00:13:12,000
He had just won the victory in Montgomery.

87
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:22,000
And when he gave his panoramic treatment of history and I was talking about the times of the Greeks and Egyptians and all that good stuff.

88
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:28,000
And he said, but this is the greatest time for me and for all of us to be alive.

89
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:34,000
And he spoke about the hope that he had for America and the eradication of racism.

90
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:50,000
I never shall forget. He ended that great speech that night by saying, I have the dream that the day will come when all of God's children from base black to troubled white will be significant on the Constitution's keyboard.

91
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:57,000
And I have a copy of that speech in my possession now that I heard him deliver.

92
00:13:57,000 --> 00:14:06,000
And on that Sunday morning of the Convention, believe it or not, I worship at this church.

93
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:10,000
I came back to be pastor of Lillard, I know.

94
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:12,000
And the name of this church is just...

95
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:19,000
Third Baptist Church, which is the oldest predominant African-American Baptist Church in Western United States.

96
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:37,000
And it was founded in August, August the 1st of 1852, which was the centennial of the abolition of slavery in the Caribbean Island.

97
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:42,000
So this church also had a great conference with history.

98
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:50,000
That's the same year that Harry Beecher Stowe's book, Onka Tom's Cabin, was published.

99
00:14:50,000 --> 00:15:02,000
And I'm confident that there was agitation in there, a move for self-determination on part of blacks before the Civil War here in the West.

100
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:15,000
And that's why Eliza Davis, your husband William and others moved out of white first Baptist, white first Baptist was founded in 1849.

101
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:19,000
They moved out because they met discrimination in the church.

102
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:26,000
And they decided that they wanted to worship God indignate and not in immatilation.

103
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:35,000
And I've been pastor of this church since 1976.

104
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:42,000
Now, how did I get here? I had some intermittent stops.

105
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:44,000
What was it?

106
00:15:45,000 --> 00:15:47,000
Well, it was a good one.

107
00:15:47,000 --> 00:15:48,000
And your father was a pastor.

108
00:15:48,000 --> 00:15:58,000
And I'm wondering if you could talk a little bit about being raised in that family earlier before when we were talking about books on your father's bookshelves.

109
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:13,000
And I'm wondering if you could talk about how your family talked with you about race or race consciousness or involvement in movement to better the place of African-Americans.

110
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:21,000
Actually, I had very little conversation with my father.

111
00:16:21,000 --> 00:16:25,000
Because he was very busy. He was a country-attentive preacher.

112
00:16:25,000 --> 00:16:32,000
And he worked as a janitor.

113
00:16:32,000 --> 00:16:35,000
He was aware of the movement.

114
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:39,000
He was definitely aware of discrimination.

115
00:16:40,000 --> 00:16:45,000
But in terms of his telling me, you must get involved and do this. He didn't operate that way.

116
00:16:45,000 --> 00:16:59,000
It was of my charge and because of my exposure to people like Megavars, John W. Dixon, who was superintendent of the Sunday School and Ferris Street Baptist Church there in Jackson.

117
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:05,000
Miss Esse Collins, as I mentioned earlier, who was the treasurer of the Jackson Brannes.

118
00:17:05,000 --> 00:17:10,000
Miss Mary Cox, who wrote insurance, never wrote a bus.

119
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:20,000
She walked every place she went because she said she would not ride any bus in segregated emulation.

120
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:30,000
And Carse Hall, a letter carrier, and was an attorney.

121
00:17:30,000 --> 00:17:37,000
Went to night school and came an attorney.

122
00:17:37,000 --> 00:17:43,000
Samuel Bailey was the advisor of our youth council.

123
00:17:43,000 --> 00:17:47,000
He was a member of the College of Baptist Church. Let me say parenthetically.

124
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:55,000
Back in the day, there were only about three or four churches that embraced the civilized movement.

125
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:04,000
The other pastors and churches were a theologically conservative and didn't want to become involved.

126
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:10,000
They were only concerned about the saving of souls and getting people ready for heaven.

127
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:24,000
However, there were these churches, Ferris Street, that I was reared in, baptized there by Reverend Chester Arthur Greer from Fort Worth, Texas.

128
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:37,000
There was Pearl Street African Methodist Episcopal Church, passed by Reverend Gerr Horton.

129
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:47,000
There was College Hill Baptist Church, passed by Reverend W. L. Jones.

130
00:18:47,000 --> 00:19:03,000
And later, the new Mount Zion Baptist Church, that Reverend Bale became pastor of during the height of the student demonstrations of the 60s.

131
00:19:04,000 --> 00:19:08,000
Those were all the churches who would open their doors.

132
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:11,000
Out of how many in Jackson?

133
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:21,000
Oh my God. You must have had about 100 more churches. People were afraid.

134
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:42,000
We were mavericks. And literally, I know also that the State Sovereignty Commission, that watch the spying group on all civil rights workers, had a 10-page file on me.

135
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:50,000
When that file was open in the 1980s.

136
00:19:50,000 --> 00:20:05,000
We knew that we were being watched, but we didn't think that they were that serious in terms of spending money to spy on teenagers, kids, but even had a report in that file.

137
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:07,000
Now, I will give you a copy of it.

138
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:16,000
In which it was reported that I had opened a bank account at the deposit guaranteed bank.

139
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:32,000
One of the vice presidents broke the law, broke confidentiality, and reported to Mayor Thompson and to the chief of police that I had opened this bank account.

140
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:35,000
And the amount of money that we deposited.

141
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:44,000
And there was a notation there that this name must be kept confidential and they had blotted out the name.

142
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:47,000
His name was LATAM.

143
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:57,000
LATAM. I don't know if he's still alive or not, but he was a vice president of the deposit guaranteed bank of Jackson.

144
00:20:57,000 --> 00:21:08,000
They also had on file that any place that I spoke as president of the youth council has later state president of youth councils in Mississippi.

145
00:21:08,000 --> 00:21:21,000
Any conventions that I went to, in fact, it was in 1958, again with Mr. Avers and Mr. Joseph Broadwater, who was a member of our branch.

146
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:27,000
We went to the convention in Cleveland.

147
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:33,000
That was the year that the Little Rock Nine won the Nobel Peace Prize.

148
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:49,000
And I was in an interview with the Cleveland Plain Dealer paper about conditions of blacks in Mississippi and the double system of education we had.

149
00:21:49,000 --> 00:21:55,000
And the fact that black teachers were not receiving salaries equal to whites.

150
00:21:55,000 --> 00:22:00,000
And someone, I can give you a cup of that, dog.

151
00:22:00,000 --> 00:22:13,000
Someone sent to the white superintendent, Mr. Kirby Walker, Kirby P. Walker.

152
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:17,000
That article.

153
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:32,000
And I was told when I got back home in the school that fall going into my senior year in 1959 at Jim Hill High School, that segregated school.

154
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:54,000
I was told by my principal, Mr. Luther Marshall, that he had gotten orders from the white superintendent and the black superintendent of schools that I was to not be permitted to re-enroll and Jim Hill High School.

155
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:02,000
I was told to keep my mouth shut and I was creating too much trouble.

156
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:15,000
Well, when Megahevers again, my mentor heard about this, he got with my mother and later contacted my father, who was, by the way, at the National Baptist Convention,

157
00:23:15,000 --> 00:23:19,000
in September when school opened up.

158
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:27,000
And we threatened to follow a lawsuit for the deterioration of, of pro-vine high school.

159
00:23:27,000 --> 00:23:30,000
That's a white high school that near my home.

160
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:44,000
And all of this is written up in Mr. Evers' biography, that book by Man in Marvel's and the biography.

161
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:47,000
It was autobiography, excuse me, of Megahevers?

162
00:23:47,000 --> 00:23:51,000
Well, all of this is documented in that book.

163
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:57,000
And when Mr. Evers threatened the suit, they really started moving in.

164
00:23:57,000 --> 00:24:00,000
They didn't want to integrate the schools.

165
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:07,000
And so they rescinded my being prohibited from going to Jim Hill.

166
00:24:07,000 --> 00:24:09,000
They let me back in.

167
00:24:09,000 --> 00:24:18,000
But they abolished the student council that I was also president of in order to break my influence.

168
00:24:18,000 --> 00:24:26,000
I have a, the students later elected me president of the senior class.

169
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:31,000
Well, they would help my holding their position.

170
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:36,000
And I was valedictorian.

171
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:44,000
But again, to break my spirit, they denied me that honor.

172
00:24:44,000 --> 00:24:49,000
And only let me be salutatorian.

173
00:24:49,000 --> 00:24:51,000
Now, what's your principle?

174
00:24:51,000 --> 00:24:54,000
What's, what's, what's, where these his decisions or what's he being told to?

175
00:24:54,000 --> 00:24:59,000
He's been told, in fact, years later, after I had gone, finished more house,

176
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:05,000
crows of seminary, I had become an accomplished pastor.

177
00:25:05,000 --> 00:25:12,000
I went back home and he saw me and he broke down and started crying.

178
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:16,000
He said to me, Brown, you were a kid then.

179
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:24,000
And you didn't understand that we were on a lot of pressure, on a lot of threats.

180
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:27,000
And we were afraid of losing our jobs.

181
00:25:28,000 --> 00:25:32,000
He said, I don't mean interpersonal harm against you.

182
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:37,000
He said, but I had to do what the people told me to do.

183
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:43,000
And it was that kind of an atmosphere, and Mr. Simpich back there.

184
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:52,000
In fact, in that state's Obnacomission report, there was an indication of how they had spies

185
00:25:53,000 --> 00:26:00,000
who would go to any mass meeting and would take down the license plate numbers

186
00:26:00,000 --> 00:26:05,000
of anybody's car who was parked around the church.

187
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:08,000
And they would find out who the car belonged to.

188
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:16,000
And the next week, they would research where you work and you would get a notice

189
00:26:17,000 --> 00:26:24,000
that you would fire for being involved with civil rights activity.

190
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:33,000
I continued my involvement in the NAACP Youth Movement and was elected National Chairman

191
00:26:34,000 --> 00:26:39,000
of the Youth Work Committee in 1959 in New York City.

192
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:43,000
Again, Dr. King was at that meeting.

193
00:26:43,000 --> 00:26:50,000
And it was there that Pitcher was taken of Royal Wilkins, the then Executive Secretary

194
00:26:50,000 --> 00:26:56,000
and Dr. King and myself as Chairman of the National Youth Work Committee.

195
00:26:56,000 --> 00:27:07,000
And it was that meeting that I presided over the report things of all youth units in the nation.

196
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:20,000
And I was privileged to receive the report from Clara Looper, who was the advisor of Oklahoma City Youth Council

197
00:27:20,000 --> 00:27:27,000
and Bob Rapose, who was the president of the Youth Council in Oklahoma City.

198
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:34,000
These two personages reported on their successes in Oklahoma City.

199
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:48,000
Again, that magic number August 28th, August 28th, 1958, was when there was the first sit-down movement

200
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:55,000
in an organized mass way by young blacks on the umbrella of NAACP.

201
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:59,000
You see, in this country, we have romanticized the student city movement.

202
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:08,000
The student city movement did not begin in Greensboro, 1960.

203
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:13,000
It started in Oklahoma City, August 28th, 1958.

204
00:28:13,000 --> 00:28:19,000
And at that meeting, back to my point about my presiding in New York, in 1959,

205
00:28:19,000 --> 00:28:28,000
according to the report of the credentials committee of the NAACP that's on record at the Library of Congress,

206
00:28:28,000 --> 00:28:37,000
there was a young man named Izella Blair, who was an alternate youth-gut delegate to the convention.

207
00:28:37,000 --> 00:28:44,000
He heard Bob Rapose, Clara Looper, reporting about what they had done in Oklahoma City.

208
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:54,000
And when he went back to Greensboro, that fall of 1959 entering as a freshman at A&D College,

209
00:28:54,000 --> 00:28:59,000
he started telling his fellow classmates about this movement.

210
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:14,000
And no one would move with him during the fall, but he got three others to go with him and sit down on February of the first, 1960.

211
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:30,000
And then the movement began to spread like wildfire across the South, to Nashville, to Tallahassee, to Patten Rouge, to Atlanta.

212
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:34,000
And that's the real acquistor.

213
00:29:34,000 --> 00:29:41,000
I'm working now to write a book entitled Before 1960.

214
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:52,000
To put it all an accurate historical perspective of when, what was then called, the student sit down,

215
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:56,000
it was called sit-in, it was called sit-down movement.

216
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:10,000
And this movement of 1958, it was also replicated in which starcansers, Louis Vigatucche, all youth units of NAACP.

217
00:30:10,000 --> 00:30:25,000
And we had laid, by the way, the groundwork for this, here in San Francisco in 1956, on the leadership of Herbert Wright, who was then the National Youth Secretary.

218
00:30:25,000 --> 00:30:28,000
He's still alive, he lives up in Connecticut.

219
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:33,000
He was reared in the Houston, Texas branch.

220
00:30:33,000 --> 00:30:46,000
And he got us engaged in student youth activism.

221
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:55,000
And this was written up in the Tokyo Times, the London Times, the New York Times,

222
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:02,000
all the major papers around the world. But the American press sat on what happened and tried to wipe it out.

223
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:07,000
Forget about it, in 1958.

224
00:31:07,000 --> 00:31:15,000
I think it's such an important part of the story is that NAACP youth training that the Greensboro guys had,

225
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:19,000
also that, you know, that Rosa Parks was the training that Rosa Parks had.

226
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:21,000
People get that story.

227
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:33,000
His thing about Duke, this park worked as a secretary of the Montgomery NAACP.

228
00:31:33,000 --> 00:31:36,000
And she was advisor to the Youth Council.

229
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:44,000
Now, he was a connection that brought me into the loop.

230
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:48,000
I met Dr. King here in San Francisco in 1956.

231
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:51,000
There was a year of the victory of the Montgomery movement.

232
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:57,000
There were delgas from the Montgomery branch.

233
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:05,000
But what happened? In 1956, the state of Alabama sought to wipe out NAACP's

234
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:11,000
and they made it illegal for NAACP to function in Alabama.

235
00:32:11,000 --> 00:32:20,000
And that's why Dr. King and others had to organize the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.

236
00:32:20,000 --> 00:32:25,000
So they went under the umbrella of the Faith Community.

237
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:31,000
They were smart enough to say, if you won't let us function as a civil rights advocacy organization in Alabama,

238
00:32:31,000 --> 00:32:36,000
you can't mess with our churches and our religion.

239
00:32:36,000 --> 00:32:41,000
That's exactly how the Southern Christian Leadership Conference came into being.

240
00:32:41,000 --> 00:32:54,000
But back to your point about Rosa Parks, her being involved was started on the umbrella of NAACP

241
00:32:55,000 --> 00:33:04,000
and serving as an advisor to the Youth Council in Montgomery, Alabama.

242
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:08,000
Just a quick pause.

243
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:19,000
Could you tell us how you first got to know Mr. Evers and developed this relationship with him?

244
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:27,000
As I lose you earlier, I became aware of who he was through my sister Gloria Holiday, who's still living.

245
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:31,000
She lives in Denver, Colorado.

246
00:33:31,000 --> 00:33:43,000
And Mr. Evers was a very humble, warm, engaging man.

247
00:33:43,000 --> 00:33:50,000
And we discovered my interest, my talents, my ability, even as a lad.

248
00:33:50,000 --> 00:33:53,000
He encouraged me.

249
00:33:53,000 --> 00:34:02,000
He sort of was my surrogate father, elder brother.

250
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:11,000
And he made sure that I had opportunities to go to meetings wherever they were.

251
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:19,000
And my mother, who was President responsible for me, because my father's, I said, travel a lot.

252
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:24,000
But she never questioned Mr. Evers.

253
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:27,000
She never expressed it. She did have any fear.

254
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:29,000
She never expressed it.

255
00:34:29,000 --> 00:34:34,000
She would always say, well, if that's what you want to do, go ahead.

256
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:36,000
I'm with you.

257
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:41,000
And Mr. Evers took me to all these meetings.

258
00:34:41,000 --> 00:34:44,000
We even went up to the Mississippi Delta.

259
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:53,000
And there were points when we disguised ourselves as sharecroppers to hold mass meetings,

260
00:34:53,000 --> 00:34:57,000
or to investigate cases.

261
00:34:57,000 --> 00:35:01,000
And we were all over the state.

262
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:04,000
You mentioned fear.

263
00:35:04,000 --> 00:35:07,000
Did you experience fear in situations like that?

264
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:08,000
Not really.

265
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:12,000
I guess I was too young, maybe too daring, too naive.

266
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:16,000
I wasn't scared at all.

267
00:35:16,000 --> 00:35:22,000
But as I looked back on what I know about what the State Cyber and Commission was doing,

268
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:27,000
my life was really in harm's way.

269
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:32,000
The State Cyber and Commission in that file that I mentioned,

270
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:37,000
gave a summation report after they had all these details over.

271
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:43,000
And a documentation of what I had done.

272
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:51,000
Amos Brown is a full-fledged agitator.

273
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:58,000
And this is the report on him that we must keep active.

274
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:07,000
Wherever I was arrested, they had a record of that,

275
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:12,000
whether it was in Atlanta, Savannah, Georgia.

276
00:36:12,000 --> 00:36:17,000
I let away the end of the time and beach there.

277
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:25,000
Also, I desegregated first Baptist Church of Atlanta.

278
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:29,000
Dr. Benjamin Mays wrote about that in his writings.

279
00:36:29,000 --> 00:36:34,000
At church, there's now passed by Reverend Charles Stanley.

280
00:36:34,000 --> 00:36:39,000
Back in 1961, did not admit black people there.

281
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:41,000
In fact, that's where I met my wife.

282
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:43,000
She was a student at Spellman.

283
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:48,000
The white students at Georgia Tech,

284
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:56,000
more-how students, led a kneel-in rather kneel-in once on the morning.

285
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:01,000
And at that church, Deacons and Trustees literally picked up these students

286
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:05,000
and threw them out of that church.

287
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:10,000
And after the service was over, I showed my wife outside on the steps

288
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:13,000
with a number of other wives to be there.

289
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:17,000
It is a number of other students at Spellman.

290
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:24,000
So every kind of demonstration to break down barriers, I was part of it.

291
00:37:24,000 --> 00:37:27,000
And you were a more-how student than your graduate from high school.

292
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:28,000
Yeah.

293
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:34,000
I was a part of the leadership contingency of the Senate movement

294
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:37,000
in Atlanta, along with Marin Wright,

295
00:37:37,000 --> 00:37:41,000
Elliman, who now is over the Children's Fence Fund.

296
00:37:41,000 --> 00:37:47,000
In fact, she wrote a book entitled Lanterns.

297
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:52,000
And in that book is a chapter where she mentions me.

298
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:57,000
She said there was a young, bright, in ACP,

299
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:00,000
a name Amos Brown in the room,

300
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:05,000
when we met with the college presidents to let them know

301
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:08,000
that we were going to sit in.

302
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:13,000
You see, when we decided to get them out in the movement,

303
00:38:13,000 --> 00:38:18,000
all of the college presidents of those black schools called us in,

304
00:38:18,000 --> 00:38:22,000
because they knew we were going to join with other students throughout the South.

305
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:26,000
And they said, we're not going to try and discourage you

306
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:30,000
or block your activity.

307
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:35,000
But you ought to let the world know why you're doing what you're doing.

308
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:41,000
And it was Dr. Rufus Cleman and Dr. Mayes who suggested

309
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:49,000
that we would write a document explaining why I raised in that term,

310
00:38:49,000 --> 00:38:52,000
but what we were doing.

311
00:38:52,000 --> 00:38:57,000
And they said, we will raise the money to pay for your document

312
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:04,000
to be published in the Atlanta Journal Constitution.

313
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:07,000
And I was a part of that committee.

314
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:10,000
I was the youngest one in the room.

315
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:16,000
The other persons in the room were Lonnie King, who still alive.

316
00:39:16,000 --> 00:39:20,000
Charles Black, who still alive.

317
00:39:20,000 --> 00:39:25,000
Her shelf Sullivan, Julian Bond,

318
00:39:26,000 --> 00:39:29,000
and Mary and Wright Elliman,

319
00:39:29,000 --> 00:39:33,000
it's Don Klaug, who's a Klaug, A.U.

320
00:39:33,000 --> 00:39:36,000
among others. We went in that room.

321
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:39,000
And after we wrote that document,

322
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:44,000
it's entitled the Committee on Appeal for Human Rights.

323
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:47,000
And it was published in the Journal.

324
00:39:47,000 --> 00:39:54,000
We sat in, and I spent time in jail with Dr. Martin Luther King,

325
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:59,000
his brother, A.D., oldest mouse, still alive,

326
00:39:59,000 --> 00:40:04,000
past the Maritus of the Oliver Baptist Church of Cleveland,

327
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:12,000
Ohio, and Lonnie King, and David Satcher.

328
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:18,000
David Satcher, the former Surgeon General of the United States.

329
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:21,000
We were schoolmates at Moor House.

330
00:40:22,000 --> 00:40:29,000
Like we lived in the same dorm, our junior year, May is home.

331
00:40:29,000 --> 00:40:34,000
We entered the Moor House at the same time too.

332
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:38,000
So that was my experience.

333
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:42,000
But my experience was not just relegated to civil rights in America.

334
00:40:42,000 --> 00:40:47,000
I became aware of world affairs.

335
00:40:48,000 --> 00:40:56,000
In 1957, when I met Raj Mahan Gandhi,

336
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:01,000
Mahatma Gandhi's grandson, he was here in the United States

337
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:06,000
with an organization called Moral Rearmament.

338
00:41:06,000 --> 00:41:12,000
It was founded by Dr. Buchmann in England.

339
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:16,000
It's called the Oxford Movement back in the 40s.

340
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:21,000
And they had the, what I consider to be a bit naive,

341
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:26,000
that the world would be made better if people just commit themselves

342
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:33,000
to some absolutes, absolute honesty, absolute purity.

343
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:38,000
I absolutely non-sabious at all this.

344
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:43,000
Well, I listened to it, and I saw some good in it.

345
00:41:43,000 --> 00:41:55,000
But I felt back then that you needed some realistic, legislative action

346
00:41:55,000 --> 00:42:02,000
to change the legal underpinnings for discrimination in this country.

347
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:06,000
In addition to calling on the individual to change one's heart

348
00:42:06,000 --> 00:42:12,000
and try to live a higher standard of living.

349
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:19,000
And later, after I went to that world affairs camp meeting

350
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:27,000
up at Mackinac Island, Michigan, Mr. Gandhi invited me to be his guest.

351
00:42:27,000 --> 00:42:32,000
And there were about 87 countries reputed from around the world.

352
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:41,000
That was the same year that Martin Luther King won the Spingarm Medal,

353
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:46,000
which is the highest medal that could be bestowed on an African-American

354
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:53,000
for achievement in previous years in that particular calendar year.

355
00:42:53,000 --> 00:42:59,000
And Mr. Gandhi was there to be a part of that ceremony.

356
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:07,000
And then from that international exposure, I also was invited in 1958

357
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:18,000
by the Quakers to attend a world affairs camp at Camp Dandy near Cornell University.

358
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:20,000
It's been a whole summer there.

359
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:23,000
Here I was, kid out of Mississippi.

360
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:26,000
My parents went there from a fluent.

361
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:36,000
Although we were poor in things, we were rich in ideas and academic pursuits

362
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:44,000
and commitment to social engineering and social justice.

363
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:47,000
So that's been basically my career.

364
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:52,000
And since then, this has been my passion.

365
00:43:52,000 --> 00:43:59,000
I was given a scholarship when I finished Morehouse in 1964 to go to Africa.

366
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:02,000
That was my first trip to Africa.

367
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:05,000
1950.

368
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:08,000
1964.

369
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:11,000
Yeah.

370
00:44:11,000 --> 00:44:22,000
So that was the year that I finished Morehouse and also my year of being admitted

371
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:28,000
to Crow's Theological Seminary for my Theological Training.

372
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:34,000
And by the way, one of my letters, the recommendations, was written by Dr. King.

373
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:37,000
He actually studied with Dr. King at Morehouse.

374
00:44:37,000 --> 00:44:39,000
Yes, I did.

375
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:43,000
But when I went to graduate school, he wrote one of my letters of recommendation.

376
00:44:43,000 --> 00:44:46,000
He went to Crow's Theological Seminary back in 1948.

377
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:53,000
I have a picture of him at the Calvary Baptist Church with the Church Officers

378
00:44:53,000 --> 00:44:58,000
when he was 19 years old when he entered Crow's.

379
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:04,000
See, his father was a very close friend of Dr. J. Pius Barber.

380
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:11,000
Dr. Barber was editor of the National Baptist Voice, a graduate of Morehouse,

381
00:45:11,000 --> 00:45:14,000
native of Galveston, Texas.

382
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:18,000
His father was a preacher there in Galveston, too.

383
00:45:18,000 --> 00:45:23,000
And he finished Morehouse around 1911.

384
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:26,000
And he went to Crow's Theological Seminary.

385
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:30,000
As a second black student to finish there.

386
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:40,000
And from the time that he finished, he was the unofficial dean of all black students at Crow's Theological Seminary.

387
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:49,000
And we spent many nights in his Paula discussing politics, theology, you name it.

388
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:59,000
And he was a mentor for many great preachers who were of the prophetic, liberal tradition.

389
00:45:59,000 --> 00:46:04,000
So, his William Augustus Jones from Kentucky, he's now deceased.

390
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:13,000
He was passed to that great church in Brooklyn, New York, Bethany Baptist.

391
00:46:13,000 --> 00:46:18,000
Dr. Samuel D. Whitprockner, who went to Crow's.

392
00:46:18,000 --> 00:46:25,000
Dr. Harold Carter, who still alive, is in Baltimore, Maryland.

393
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:31,000
Dr. B. J. Whipper, Shr. Malabama.

394
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:36,000
Dr. Charles Booth, is in Columbus, Ohio.

395
00:46:36,000 --> 00:46:44,000
Dr. Jesse Wendell Mapson, is passed in Philadelphia.

396
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:55,000
Reverend Dr. Archie Lamone, who served with the World Council of Churches in Geneva, Switzerland.

397
00:46:55,000 --> 00:47:19,000
When his having finished Seminary and this tradition is what created African-American preachers' prophets who own the cutting edge and never bifurcated the gospel.

398
00:47:19,000 --> 00:47:25,000
There was never either a personal celebration or social celebration.

399
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:27,000
It was always both and.

400
00:47:27,000 --> 00:47:45,000
We could not see at all how one could talk about saving a soul and not dealing with the society that made it difficult for the soul to be armable just and fair.

401
00:47:45,000 --> 00:47:48,000
We did not get a deal with both.

402
00:47:48,000 --> 00:47:57,000
That is why we got the blessing and the gift of Mordecai-Wire Johnson.

403
00:47:57,000 --> 00:48:01,000
He too finished Morehouse College.

404
00:48:01,000 --> 00:48:10,000
And went to Coguay Rochester, the sister school of Crosa.

405
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:18,000
Dr. Mordecai Johnson, born in Paris, Tennessee.

406
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:22,000
He studied at Harvard, University of Chicago.

407
00:48:22,000 --> 00:48:32,000
But he was pastor of the first Baptist Church in Charleston, West Virginia in 1926.

408
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:43,000
Before 1926, the Board of Trustees did not have a confidence in any black who could be president of that school.

409
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:47,000
But they decided that they were giving out an opportunity.

410
00:48:47,000 --> 00:49:01,000
And when they sent out the search committee, people like Ralph Bunch, Sterling Brown and others, they felt that they were scholars and they should have been considered.

411
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:12,000
But the prevailing wisdom was that they needed a personality like Dr. Mordecai Johnson to lead that school and take it to its next level.

412
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:17,000
He was elected president in 1926.

413
00:49:17,000 --> 00:49:34,000
When he got there, his first agenda item was to discover what could be done to bring that law school to first class status.

414
00:49:34,000 --> 00:49:38,000
It was a night school when he got there.

415
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:48,000
What did he do? He called on Justice Lewis Brandeis, who served on the Supreme Court.

416
00:49:48,000 --> 00:49:55,000
And he asked him, if you were to build a first class law school, what would you advise the builder to do?

417
00:49:55,000 --> 00:50:05,000
And on the condition that Justice, that Mr. Reverend Dr. Johnson would not tell him what he said until he died, he told him,

418
00:50:05,000 --> 00:50:18,000
I would build a law school that would teach young black lawyers how to become corporate lawyers to make money for them, say, a criminal lawyer.

419
00:50:18,000 --> 00:50:39,000
He said, I would build a great school that would teach young black minds how to master the art of constitutional law.

420
00:50:40,000 --> 00:51:00,000
And from that conversation, Dr. Johnson sought out Charles Hamilton Houston and gave him the green light to build a law school, making first class.

421
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:04,000
And then Charles Hamilton Houston's first class.

422
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:20,000
There were three young men, Thurgood Marshall from Vautamor, Maryland, who had been denied admission to the University of Maryland law school.

423
00:51:21,000 --> 00:51:28,000
Oliver Heel from Richmond, Virginia, Robert Carter from Montclair, New Jersey.

424
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:37,000
And there was the council and the mentorship of one James Napier.

425
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:51,000
It was that team that went before the Supreme Court, beginning in 1953, got involved in developing the briefs.

426
00:51:51,000 --> 00:52:05,000
And they went and argued so persuasively against the backdrop and the buttress of the 14th Amendment, equal protection on the law, making the case

427
00:52:05,000 --> 00:52:21,000
that segregated public education was not equal and they denied it, denied black children equal protection on the law.

428
00:52:21,000 --> 00:52:38,000
That amendment brought us over and broke down the legal barriers for discrimination in this country, reverse, plethora versus Ferguson.

429
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:54,000
So we owe it to Dr. Johnson, the foundation of the black church, for all that we have achieved, not the total church, because not everybody was involved in the movement.

430
00:52:54,000 --> 00:53:05,000
In fact, the joint center for political studies came out with reports some time ago, not only about 3% of the black preachers were involved in civil rights movement.

431
00:53:05,000 --> 00:53:10,000
It's a romanticized statement to say that everybody was with Dr. Kim. They were not.

432
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:17,000
For as I mentioned to you earlier, there were about three or four churches in my own town of Jackson, Mississippi, who became in the movement.

433
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:23,000
And Dr. Kim was a remnant of this group.

434
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:28,000
He was a new breed, just a handful.

435
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:34,000
And then Florida, there was CK Steel in Tallahassem.

436
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:43,000
And my aunt and father Gibson, in Tampa, alien Laurie.

437
00:53:43,000 --> 00:53:50,000
And of course Tennessee, you had Benjamin Lawson Hooks.

438
00:53:50,000 --> 00:53:56,000
And Dr. Ones and Metropolitan.

439
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:02,000
In Georgia, you had Samuel Woodrow Williams, who was college minister.

440
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:08,000
And he co-team taught that course, that seminar in social philosophy with Dr. King that I mentioned earlier.

441
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:18,000
And his college minister at Morehouse, and was pastor of the oldest black Baptist church in Atlanta, friendship Baptist.

442
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:22,000
Can you talk a little bit more about that class that you were in with them?

443
00:54:22,000 --> 00:54:25,000
Oh, that was an exciting class.

444
00:54:25,000 --> 00:54:28,000
It was small, only eight of us.

445
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:32,000
And Dr. King was very down to earth.

446
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:34,000
There was nothing arrogant about him.

447
00:54:34,000 --> 00:54:36,000
He was a regular brother.

448
00:54:36,000 --> 00:54:39,000
He was a brilliant man.

449
00:54:39,000 --> 00:54:49,000
And it was just an incredible experience to see it at his feet.

450
00:54:49,000 --> 00:54:59,000
And one thing I remember about that class is he was talking about the theory of personalism.

451
00:54:59,000 --> 00:55:09,000
The he acquired from Brightman at Boston University, when he was studying his PhD degree, where he got his PhD.

452
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:13,000
We all know in systematic theology.

453
00:55:13,000 --> 00:55:22,000
Personalism that every human being is immune with dignity and worth.

454
00:55:22,000 --> 00:55:28,000
And we should respect that worth and dignity.

455
00:55:28,000 --> 00:55:42,000
And not in rate, not in measure of judge people on the basis of where I was born, where I was one's color, what one religion was.

456
00:55:42,000 --> 00:55:50,000
But we should respect every person in spite of our unixes and differences.

457
00:55:50,000 --> 00:56:11,000
And that's why, even in my own time, it was not difficult for me to embrace women preachers, though about 98% of black preachers who against white oppression have been against women.

458
00:56:11,000 --> 00:56:13,000
My church, I have women preachers.

459
00:56:13,000 --> 00:56:28,000
I have our day in the first woman preacher in this city, in this church, in 1984, where I women deacon, women involved throughout leadership team of this church.

460
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:40,000
And when the issue came up regarding gay rights, I had had a problem because I didn't knew what my teacher would do.

461
00:56:40,000 --> 00:57:03,000
If he were here today, and I felt that it was wrong for us to codify one's rights, the rights of a people who have been marginalized, for they to deserve equal protection under the law.

462
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:06,000
Yet so many other churches didn't.

463
00:57:06,000 --> 00:57:13,000
They did not, because they did not understand our king and they did not know how we got over.

464
00:57:13,000 --> 00:57:22,000
You see John Mercer Langston back in 1866.

465
00:57:23,000 --> 00:57:34,000
This is the great uncle of Langston Hughes, who was the first black to serve in Congress during reconstruction from Virginia.

466
00:57:34,000 --> 00:57:47,000
And he and Charles Satchel, the first black pastor of Third Baptist, were in the leadership of the abolitionist movement in Ohio before 1850.

467
00:57:47,000 --> 00:57:57,000
Back at my point, I have a copy of a speech that John Mercer Langston delivered in St. Louis, Missouri in 1866.

468
00:57:57,000 --> 00:58:03,000
And you know what I tell you guys people? Equal protection before the law.

469
00:58:03,000 --> 00:58:13,000
And he was fighting an organ for blacks to have the right to vote back then.

470
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:25,000
And he said among other things, if you feel that black folks must be educated, must be learned, know how to read and write, make sure that all white folks are required to do the same.

471
00:58:25,000 --> 00:58:32,000
Because there are many of them who are in franchise who are voting.

472
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:40,000
That was something that really shook me away back then.

473
00:58:40,000 --> 00:58:54,000
He was this man, a preacher and a lawyer who labored along with my predecessor, Charles Satchel, for equality of opportunity.

474
00:58:54,000 --> 00:59:04,000
So I told all of my brothers who were not aware of this kind of history, were not aware of this kind of reasoning.

475
00:59:04,000 --> 00:59:10,000
You know, you must not become that which you hate.

476
00:59:10,000 --> 00:59:23,000
And if you hate, they're like the fact that white folks discriminated against you because of color your skin, don't discriminate against gay, lesbian, transgender.

477
00:59:23,000 --> 00:59:29,000
And you're not going to be a white, a bisexual people because they're different.

478
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:33,000
And I pushed your eyes in that notion that we are all different.

479
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:50,000
As long as we're not violating the law during the injury harmed anyone, we should not legislate how people are to experience their own life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness.

480
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:57,000
And I tried to impact upon them the fact that, in principle, the rather, that I'm heterosexual.

481
00:59:57,000 --> 01:00:00,000
That's who I am.

482
01:00:00,000 --> 01:00:05,000
Gays and lesbians, transgender, bisexual people, that's who they are.

483
01:00:05,000 --> 01:00:07,000
And we must not generalize on them.

484
01:00:07,000 --> 01:00:18,000
And I remind them often that the divorce rate in America is the highest, not in California, not in New England, but the Unitarians are on the Liberals.

485
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:29,000
Not out here where they think we're cooking crazy, but the divorce rate in America is the highest in the Bible belt, where we sing the most, shout the most, preach the most, go to church the most.

486
01:00:29,000 --> 01:00:38,000
And I always raise the relic of a question to them, how can you blame other people for not being able to keep your own relationship together?

487
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:47,000
I said, why is it that an Alabama, Mississippi, Georgia, Florida, Tennessee, South Carolina, North Carolina, up into Oklahoma.

488
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:56,000
The divorce rate in this nation is the highest amongst religious church-going people.

489
01:00:56,000 --> 01:00:57,000
Can't explain it.

490
01:00:57,000 --> 01:01:12,000
And then I remind them also, in terms of respect and the worth of the dignity of all people, the King James, who gave us the King James translation in the Bible, that many of them loved to hear.

491
01:01:12,000 --> 01:01:16,000
These and the dolls, the old Chaucer in English, you know.

492
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:21,000
I said, did you know that King James was gay?

493
01:01:21,000 --> 01:01:25,000
And I really had them there, and on which way to run.

494
01:01:25,000 --> 01:01:31,000
I said, because he was gay and he made this contribution, are you going to burn up all the Bible?

495
01:01:31,000 --> 01:01:33,000
I think we should be aware.

496
01:01:33,000 --> 01:01:45,000
I said, now that does not mean that you are not entitled to decide what you're going to do about marriage equality, in context of your religious rights, RITES.

497
01:01:45,000 --> 01:01:54,000
There's a difference between religious rights and the rights that we are guaranteed under Constitution and the laws of the state.

498
01:01:54,000 --> 01:01:57,000
And I said, you cannot discriminate against people.

499
01:01:57,000 --> 01:02:21,000
And I reminded them also, we would not be Baptist, if we did not have the freedom to interpret the Bible in the way that we are led to do because Roger Williams in 1638 was run out of the Massachusetts Bay College, because the Puritans and the congregation said, we're going to have a state church, we're going to tell people what to believe.

500
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:25,000
He said, oh no, I'm going to have freedom of conscience.

501
01:02:25,000 --> 01:02:30,000
There'll be a separation of church and state, autonomy of the local congregation.

502
01:02:30,000 --> 01:02:39,000
And I said, are you going to deny, are you going to spit on the principles that enable you to be a Baptist?

503
01:02:40,000 --> 01:02:51,000
I said, we must not deny those persons, those congregations, the right to perform the same sex marriage, if they want to.

504
01:02:51,000 --> 01:02:54,000
I said, that may not be a part of my tradition.

505
01:02:54,000 --> 01:03:04,000
And I have that right as one living in a democratic society to follow the tradition that speaks to me.

506
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:13,000
And I said, I do not perform same sex marriage because of the tradition that I'm exposed to where I am here and now.

507
01:03:13,000 --> 01:03:32,000
But it's wrong. It's not just, it does not provide equal protection on the law for you to go out and join with forces, whether it's Catholic church or the moment to say we're going to deny these persons equal protection on the law.

508
01:03:33,000 --> 01:03:42,000
By imposing our private religious persuasions and doctrines on them.

509
01:03:42,000 --> 01:03:54,000
It's a free country. It is not a theocracy. It is a democracy, a government, a people, and for the people.

510
01:03:55,000 --> 01:04:05,000
And are those people, are gay and straight for people, black and white, brown, yellow, red, who are precious in God's sight.

511
01:04:05,000 --> 01:04:15,000
And that's what I stood on. And many didn't want to hear it. Even some of this church, finally they came around.

512
01:04:15,000 --> 01:04:26,000
And on Sunday morning, a young man who finally had to apologize to me in the whole church, tried to come up and take over the poor pit once on the morning.

513
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:32,000
When I said that I was not going to support proposition eight.

514
01:04:32,000 --> 01:04:41,000
And right now, I believe in my own way to be in vindicated because I think the change has come.

515
01:04:41,000 --> 01:04:46,000
Even the position that Mr. Obama, the president has taken.

516
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:58,000
Here again, I was the prophet as my son in school teacher told me to be, who bore the burdens of the people.

517
01:04:58,000 --> 01:05:10,000
And I think that I have, I'm born those burdens, not just for black people, not just for women, but also for gay people.

518
01:05:10,000 --> 01:05:21,000
You mentioned earlier the idea of, you mentioned earlier the idea of not only civil rights but human rights.

519
01:05:21,000 --> 01:05:25,000
Yes, can you talk about that in the context of what?

520
01:05:25,000 --> 01:05:30,000
Well, as a human rights, it takes us into the global picture.

521
01:05:30,000 --> 01:05:44,000
I think we must see that in our Christian tradition at his best, the notion is there that Christ died for the world, not for America, but for the world.

522
01:05:44,000 --> 01:05:54,000
And in that world, there are people of different cultures, different backgrounds, different religions.

523
01:05:54,000 --> 01:06:13,000
So that I must be careful about my economics, my politics here at home, in terms of seeing how they impact people who are in Bangladesh, Central America,

524
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:18,000
South America, Africa, poor people.

525
01:06:18,000 --> 01:06:29,000
You see, we're about 4% of the, one time we were six, but I made about 4% of the world population.

526
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:36,000
But we consumed 45 to 5% of the world's goods and resources.

527
01:06:36,000 --> 01:06:43,000
And yet the Bible says, the earth is the lowest, the food and the world and they dwell therein.

528
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:55,000
So it's not fair for me to support industries that are paying these horrible wages for people in China.

529
01:06:55,000 --> 01:07:07,000
These other calls, so-called Third World Nations, who are working cheap labor to support our standard of living.

530
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:14,000
What happens over in these countries does come back to impact us.

531
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:22,000
Dr. King also says, injustice anywhere, if everybody gets around the effect in all of us, everywhere.

532
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:27,000
And that's the reason why he wrote the letter from the Birmingham jail.

533
01:07:27,000 --> 01:07:34,000
Remember the white clergy of Birmingham said, you don't need to be coming here stirring up trouble, you don't live here.

534
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:43,000
You don't pay taxes here. Get out of town, Dr. King. Stay in your own pool pit up there in Atlanta.

535
01:07:44,000 --> 01:07:55,000
But he wrote that letter to let them know that we are in this garment mutually impacted.

536
01:07:55,000 --> 01:08:04,000
And what affects one gets around the impact in us all throughout the world.

537
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:12,000
That's why we have to take this issue beyond just him civil rights for us in America.

538
01:08:12,000 --> 01:08:18,000
And look at the human rights of all people on the face of the reserve.

539
01:08:18,000 --> 01:08:22,000
And when you really go way, way back, get technical.

540
01:08:22,000 --> 01:08:34,000
Real members of the same family, according to Leakey, the paleontologist, our first home was in Africa, in the Rift Valley.

541
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:42,000
And I tell many people, when we are unkind to people of different races, we are messing with our kinfolk.

542
01:08:42,000 --> 01:08:51,000
And the only reason why we got these distinctives in terms of human features is because we migrated from one place to the other.

543
01:08:51,000 --> 01:08:55,000
And we are adjusted to the environmental conditions.

544
01:08:55,000 --> 01:09:02,000
But we must remember what my mother told me when I left home.

545
01:09:02,000 --> 01:09:14,000
Amos behaved. Unfortunately, when we left our home in Africa, we failed to behave.

546
01:09:14,000 --> 01:09:26,000
Wherever we established cultures and civilizations, we became arrogant and developed this dichotomy of them against us, against them.

547
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:32,000
Instead of getting that one little pronoun, we, we are family.

548
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:43,000
We are part of this world community. And we are going to share these resources and not be greedy and hoard unto us.

549
01:09:43,000 --> 01:09:50,000
Over our fair share, other world's resources.

550
01:09:50,000 --> 01:09:59,000
You know, if I'm having this in time of the use of these tapes, I put them on YouTube and stuff.

551
01:09:59,000 --> 01:10:11,000
Can I just, I've found this extremely moving, but another thing that was very moving was seeing hearing you talk to the youth when we, when we were first here waiting.

552
01:10:11,000 --> 01:10:20,000
Could you say something about what message you, what you're trying to convey to young people now in these times?

553
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:36,000
Well, this was a group of young men, students at Stanford, UC Berkeley, University of San Francisco, UCLA, who were pledging to be members of the Alpha Phi Alpha fraternity.

554
01:10:36,000 --> 01:10:40,000
That's also the fraternity of Dr. King, my fraternity too.

555
01:10:40,000 --> 01:10:45,000
W. B. Bush, and had a young Joseph Larrie and others.

556
01:10:45,000 --> 01:11:00,000
Well, I was trying to impress upon them that in the spirit of Alpha, we would be men of scholarship,

557
01:11:00,000 --> 01:11:07,000
man of deeds, and love for all humankind.

558
01:11:07,000 --> 01:11:12,000
And this is what Dr. King epitomized.

559
01:11:12,000 --> 01:11:15,000
First of all, he was scholar.

560
01:11:15,000 --> 01:11:21,000
He entered more house at the age of 15, the early admission student.

561
01:11:22,000 --> 01:11:31,000
Though at more house his average, and I have a copy of his transcript, he was a C plus student.

562
01:11:31,000 --> 01:11:37,000
However, at more house, those professors were hard task masters.

563
01:11:37,000 --> 01:11:45,000
When he finished more house, he went on to Crosa, and he was a nays student, was president of the student body.

564
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:51,000
When on the Boston University, he got his PhD degree. He was a scholar.

565
01:11:51,000 --> 01:12:03,000
And that's the reason why I worked here in my ministry to clone, to create more young King scholars.

566
01:12:03,000 --> 01:12:10,000
Right now, we're involved in a program over at Martin Luther King Middle School called Students of Promise,

567
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:17,000
Working with Latino and African American males who are under achieving.

568
01:12:17,000 --> 01:12:26,000
You see the mean average for all black students at the middle of high school levels in this city, believe it or not, is D plus.

569
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:33,000
And only 30% of black students in this district finish.

570
01:12:34,000 --> 01:12:36,000
30% finish high school.

571
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:43,000
And when you look at the higher education level, the same percentage obtained.

572
01:12:43,000 --> 01:12:53,000
Of those who enter school, whatever reason, drop out, on about 34% finish.

573
01:12:53,000 --> 01:12:56,000
That's tragic.

574
01:12:57,000 --> 01:13:06,000
So I was trying to let these young men know, I repeat, that they have the responsibility that once they get their sheep skin,

575
01:13:06,000 --> 01:13:15,000
don't forget that Mary McClaulathum said, when you become the first black here, the first black there, and first black there.

576
01:13:15,000 --> 01:13:18,000
Make sure you are not the last one.

577
01:13:19,000 --> 01:13:24,000
And as you climb up, reach back and pull someone along with you.

578
01:13:24,000 --> 01:13:38,000
And I was challenging them to really work to be role models, or models for young men in inner city communities.

579
01:13:38,000 --> 01:13:47,000
Secondly, I was appealing to them to be involved in the culture and the communities of the black people.

580
01:13:47,000 --> 01:14:12,000
And when you're trying middle class blacks go unto themselves and forget about the community, about reminding them that they were needed now to be what the BBB Du Bois call missionaries of culture and self-help.

581
01:14:12,000 --> 01:14:19,000
And then thirdly, I was trying to remind them that they need to be world citizens, not be provincial.

582
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:30,000
The same as I was tutored and taught to do so through the experiences that I had with Operation Crossroads Africa when I first went to Africa in 1964.

583
01:14:30,000 --> 01:14:40,000
The other thing that I did I mentioned earlier is that that program was started by a black, presbyteer pastor,

584
01:14:40,000 --> 01:14:49,000
named James Robinson, who was pastor of the Church of the Masters in Harlem in 1958.

585
01:14:49,000 --> 01:14:58,000
Same year I got in trouble with that article in Cleveland playing dealer about conditions of education in Mississippi.

586
01:14:58,000 --> 01:15:00,000
Dr. Robinson started this program.

587
01:15:00,000 --> 01:15:17,000
I was talking about engaging American and African students in summer programs of studying, travel and community development programs.

588
01:15:17,000 --> 01:15:22,000
This is where John Kennedy got the idea of the Peace Corps front.

589
01:15:22,000 --> 01:15:23,000
And where did you go?

590
01:15:23,000 --> 01:15:30,000
I went to Liberia, Sierra Leone, Senegal, and Ghana.

591
01:15:30,000 --> 01:15:35,000
It's been two and a half months there on the West Coast of Africa.

592
01:15:35,000 --> 01:15:40,000
That's my first exposure I repeat to Africa.

593
01:15:40,000 --> 01:15:47,000
And I've been to Africa since then, 22 times all over.

594
01:15:47,000 --> 01:15:57,000
And I was one of the founders along with Dr. Leon Howard Sullivan of that program called the African-American Summit.

595
01:15:57,000 --> 01:16:09,000
The first summit was held in Côte d'Arre in Avignon, Ivory Coast, about 90s, 91, who was.

596
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:20,000
And I never should have forget that night that we met in the home of Dr. Sullivan 1990.

597
01:16:20,000 --> 01:16:34,000
And he shared with us this vision of pooling African-American leaders and scholars, business persons together to build relationships across their landing.

598
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:55,000
As I was always speaking, to really help Africa go to the next level in terms of development in areas of education, economic empowerment, and community development.

599
01:16:55,000 --> 01:16:58,000
I went to many of the summits.

600
01:16:58,000 --> 01:17:07,000
How influential do you think that first experience with Operation Crossroads Africa was for you and how you view the world in your career path?

601
01:17:07,000 --> 01:17:23,000
Well, it gave me a practical experience, putting into action what I learned in 1958 at Camp D'Ambe of the Cornell University.

602
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:31,000
The Tennyson's room was right in his work, Ulysses, when he said, I am a part of all that I have met.

603
01:17:31,000 --> 01:17:37,000
We've become what we met.

604
01:17:37,000 --> 01:17:50,000
Our environment, our exposure, does create for us.

605
01:17:50,000 --> 01:17:59,000
Impressions, mirrors, use words of Charles Cooley, so say all of it, looking at ourselves.

606
01:17:59,000 --> 01:18:15,000
Our young people need more reflections in the mirror of them doing, achieving, seeing their counterparts, doing, achieving.

607
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:23,000
Unfortunately, in the Minnesota community, we don't have enough of those models.

608
01:18:23,000 --> 01:18:38,000
Crossroads was that exposure, that reflection that I began to put into action in later years with Dr. Sullivan.

609
01:18:38,000 --> 01:18:52,000
And then, here recently in the 1970s, when there was a great Cornage and War going on in Ethiopia and Eritrea.

610
01:18:52,000 --> 01:18:56,000
There were a lot of refugees from that country.

611
01:18:56,000 --> 01:19:06,000
The United States government was not fair in terms of admitting African refugees here, even though 50% of the world's refugee population was on the continent of Africa.

612
01:19:06,000 --> 01:19:11,000
Back then, the quarter for all of Africa was 790.

613
01:19:11,000 --> 01:19:18,000
But for other countries, you tell me about a minimum of at least 10,000.

614
01:19:18,000 --> 01:19:32,000
And later on, it must roomed into about 50,000 for Soviet immigrant Jewish immigrants, 125,000 for Cubans, another 45,000 Southeast Asians.

615
01:19:32,000 --> 01:19:37,000
So our immigration department was not just in fair in terms of Africa.

616
01:19:37,000 --> 01:19:45,000
And when they were challenged on it, they said, oh, we don't want to cause a brain drain on Africa.

617
01:19:45,000 --> 01:19:53,000
But they didn't say that about India. They said about these other countries. They admitted them to the country.

618
01:19:53,000 --> 01:20:06,000
So I was involved in that effort in this congregation through my leadership sponsored about 3,000 refugees from Africa and the Caribbean islands.

619
01:20:06,000 --> 01:20:18,000
In fact, the first home or haven that they received, when other churches, even black churches wouldn't receive them from Ethiopia, Eritrea, it was my home.

620
01:20:18,000 --> 01:20:37,000
My wife and I took them into our house and turned our family room into a room for refugees until we were able to get some funds to lease a two-flat Victorian house for blocks away from the church, for doors rather.

621
01:20:37,000 --> 01:20:43,000
And then later, we turned into a resellement program.

622
01:20:43,000 --> 01:20:57,000
So here again, because of the exposure, the World Fas camp, crawls rose when they needed somebody to advocate for African refugees.

623
01:20:57,000 --> 01:21:07,000
I was there and did what I could to work for their betterment and good.

624
01:21:07,000 --> 01:21:16,000
And here recently, I happened to have been invited to the 50th anniversary of the Independence of Ghana.

625
01:21:16,000 --> 01:21:33,000
And while I was there in a crawl on the last night of that celebration, just before Steve and Wander came on stage to perform, there was a young kid who performed, who was 13 years old in as a keyboard.

626
01:21:33,000 --> 01:21:37,000
