705
01:29:41,000 --> 01:29:46,000
But I told him that I passed because I wanted to finish school on time.

706
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:50,000
And I would catch him later, you know.

707
01:29:50,000 --> 01:29:57,000
But I was not shocked because I realized how tense it was.

708
01:29:57,000 --> 01:30:08,000
And he had this pre-ordination that something would happen.

709
01:30:08,000 --> 01:30:19,000
And he was too vocal and people were rallying around the calls.

710
01:30:19,000 --> 01:30:27,000
That was great protest with students from two group college, Jackson State.

711
01:30:27,000 --> 01:30:32,000
And then the freedom riders were coming later and including myself.

712
01:30:32,000 --> 01:30:43,000
The pre-wish summer in 1961, though I was not with the group that went to Montgomery.

713
01:30:43,000 --> 01:30:49,000
I went on myself on my way to Jackson.

714
01:30:49,000 --> 01:30:52,000
And did my protest.

715
01:30:52,000 --> 01:30:55,000
And I joined up with him there.

716
01:30:55,000 --> 01:31:02,000
And they had sent most of them up to parchment to the prison there.

717
01:31:02,000 --> 01:31:17,000
And so when I got there, a mechor told me that since they had already gone to the parchment, me to stay and engage young people in protests or some of the public facilities there in Jackson.

718
01:31:17,000 --> 01:31:21,000
And the one that we chose was the municipal park.

719
01:31:21,000 --> 01:31:28,000
You couldn't sit on the same bench and look at the monkeys of the elephants together with whites.

720
01:31:28,000 --> 01:31:39,000
And I was arrested at the Livingston Zoo along with several other members of the youth movement of an ACP.

721
01:31:39,000 --> 01:31:50,000
And that same summer I was arrested because I insisted that a young doctor would not call my 85-year-old neighbor boy.

722
01:31:50,000 --> 01:31:57,000
When I took him to the University of Mississippi Hospital.

723
01:31:57,000 --> 01:32:09,000
And they knew who I was because I had already been involved in demonstrations including the Livingston and Freedom Rides.

724
01:32:09,000 --> 01:32:16,000
And when Chief Ray came out that show, it was Amy's brown again.

725
01:32:16,000 --> 01:32:25,000
And the doctor told him that I had taken him on because he called my neighbor boy.

726
01:32:25,000 --> 01:32:29,000
And not a man, I bought his name.

727
01:32:29,000 --> 01:32:32,000
And they said, well what are we going to get him on now?

728
01:32:32,000 --> 01:32:41,000
And one of his, who tells us that, well we're arresting him on using profane language in public.

729
01:32:41,000 --> 01:32:44,000
And I spent two nights in jail.

730
01:32:44,000 --> 01:32:46,000
Tell me, go bail me out.

731
01:32:46,000 --> 01:32:59,000
And there's an article that ended up in the Pittsburgh Courier, which Mr. Everett said that all you have to do is open your mouth in Mississippi and it's profane.

732
01:32:59,000 --> 01:33:05,000
And that is in that State Sobbinger Commission report.

733
01:33:05,000 --> 01:33:21,000
So that was my connection with Mr. Everett during his final days.

734
01:33:21,000 --> 01:33:28,000
And I really was touched by, I was at the funeral.

735
01:33:28,000 --> 01:33:34,000
And I remember after the funeral was over, there was a march.

736
01:33:34,000 --> 01:33:50,000
And we were marching about two or three abreast behind the body before we shipped up to Washington for burial at the Arlington.

737
01:33:51,000 --> 01:34:00,000
And these whites were so inferior, in fact, that we were there in such large numbers with Niagara, Amazon, Royal Wilkins and others.

738
01:34:00,000 --> 01:34:10,000
That these police officers were using billi-clubs, hitting children, women, horses, with galloping over the funeral.

739
01:34:10,000 --> 01:34:12,000
Yes, at the funeral.

740
01:34:13,000 --> 01:34:23,000
And you were just defenseless. You couldn't do anything, but you know, you raised a hand to do anything, they were struck you down.

741
01:34:23,000 --> 01:34:31,000
But that was a horrifying experience that day, dang, in Jackson.

742
01:34:32,000 --> 01:34:42,000
So I've kept in touch with Mrs. Everett. In fact, I saw two weeks ago in New York at the National Board meeting of the HACP.

743
01:34:42,000 --> 01:35:00,000
I'm still a national board. And I will be speaking at this May on May 11th in Jackson for the Freedom Fund dinner of the Jackson branch and also for the commemorative service in Jackson.

744
01:35:02,000 --> 01:35:08,000
I've been marching the 50th year of the assassination of mechagabras.

745
01:35:08,000 --> 01:35:19,000
So was that a moment of despair for you or quickly translated into galvanizing you to carry forward?

746
01:35:20,000 --> 01:35:35,000
I've never had these moments of despair. If anything, these D2s made me more determined to continue the fight.

747
01:35:36,000 --> 01:35:53,000
And Mr. Everett would not want me to stop to be dejected, but to get up, move on.

748
01:35:53,000 --> 01:36:04,000
And that's what we must do. For this problem of race in America, it's still with us.

749
01:36:04,000 --> 01:36:15,000
And as one scholar going out west, race matters.

750
01:36:15,000 --> 01:36:33,000
It really does. Still unfortunate. And we have built a nation over a ism that should not be who well know whatever is in your DNA.

751
01:36:34,000 --> 01:36:46,000
Unless you accept treatment, a therapy, or change your lifestyle can cause your discomfort or your demise.

752
01:36:46,000 --> 01:36:54,000
As in the same thing I'm playing as America in the sense that we don't come to deal with this issue of race.

753
01:36:55,000 --> 01:37:00,000
We're going to destroy this nation.

754
01:37:00,000 --> 01:37:08,000
And we ought to move to get over it. We ought to go through the therapeutic process.

755
01:37:08,000 --> 01:37:12,000
President Bill Clinton tried to do it with his commission on race.

756
01:37:12,000 --> 01:37:17,000
That Dr. John O. Franklin was chair, but that commission was derailed.

757
01:37:17,000 --> 01:37:34,000
He was going to talk about it. And even though we have Mr. Barack Obama, the first African American to be president, we're not in the post-racial society, you know.

758
01:37:35,000 --> 01:37:49,000
It's still here. Occasion-point. Let me say this right so that I won't be here to be heartless, but I must state the facts.

759
01:37:49,000 --> 01:37:59,000
Black youth and children have lived every day in a climate of violence.

760
01:37:59,000 --> 01:38:05,000
It is more violent for an African-American male between 15 and 30.

761
01:38:05,000 --> 01:38:17,000
That was also a soldier and there's a storm, the Persian Gulf, by an Afghanistan. I'll be it now.

762
01:38:17,000 --> 01:38:26,000
At this church, I'm leading funerals, practically every month, sometimes.

763
01:38:27,000 --> 01:38:33,000
For young African-American male. It's not happening in other communities.

764
01:38:33,000 --> 01:38:40,000
And all as often as happens for us per capita.

765
01:38:41,000 --> 01:38:56,000
However, we did not get that excited about this issue of guns until 20, unfortunately, babies who have been principal of white.

766
01:38:56,000 --> 01:39:13,000
